
Cache And Persist
==================

Cache And Persist both have same purpose.
If we want to reuse the results of existing rdd then you can use then.
It will speed up the apllication by using same rdd or not computing every time.
An rdd that is not cached is re-evalutated again each time an action is invoked.

The difference between cache and persist.
cache will cache the rdd in memory.

persist comes with various storage levels.
	DISK_ONLY :- 
		Data is stored in Disk. 
		It is in serialized format. (In the form of Bytes )
		It takes less space.

	MEMORY_ONLY :- 
		Data is stored in in-memory.
		It is non-seialized format. (In the form of Object)
		It takes more space.
	
	MEMORY_ONLY_2 :- 
		This number 2 indicates 2 replias stored on 2 different workers nodes.
		Replication is useful for speeding up recovery is case one node of the cluster fails.

	MEMORY_ONLY_SER :-
		To use serilized format we use MEMORY_ONLY_SER

	MEMORY_AND_DISK :-
		It stores the data in  non-serilized format by default.
		Data is stored in in-memory, if enough memory is not available,evicted blocks from memory are stored in disk with serialized format (a.k.a eviction policy).
		These mode of operation is recommanded when re-evaluion is expensive and memory rescourses are limited.

		eviction policy :-
			consider the situation that some of the block partitions are so large (skew) that they will quick fill up the storage memory used for cacheing.
			when storage memory becomes full, an eviction policy will be used to make up the space for new blocks.
			For these it will use LRU (Least Recently Used)

	MEMORY_AND_DISK_SER :-
			To use serilized format we use	MEMORY_AND_DISK_SER		

	OFF_HEAP :-
		Blocks are cached off-heap.
		off-heap - outside the JVM
		problem with stroging the object in jvm is that it uses gc for freeing up. GC to free up the space is time taking process.
		OFF_HEAP is unsafe thing as we have to deal with raw memory outside your JVM.
		It stores in serilzses format.

Serialization increases the processing cost but reduce the memory foot print.
In non-serialization processing is bit fast but it uses more memory foot print.

Note :- 
	1. If we don't mention the storage level in persist than it work as cache.
	2. rdd.toDebugString is to check the lineage graph. And we need to read it from bottom to top.
	3. If we are using MEMORY_ONLY or cache() and our data is more than memory than it will not through any error but it will not persist any data and skip optimazation.

==========================================================================================================================

StorageLevel(True, False, False, False, 1)

useMemory=True → stored in memory

useDisk=False → not stored on disk

deserialized=True → kept as Java objects

replication=1 → single copy	




df.persist(storageLevel=DISK_ONLY)
